<p>Statistics is a powerful, fascinating, and elegant science and I enjoy sharing this with others through teaching. In addition to being a TF/TA for many courses I was formerly a <a href="http://bokcenter.harvard.edu/departmental-teaching-fellows">Departmental Teaching Fellow</a> at Harvard.</p>
<div style="font-size: 1.25em; line-height: 1.0em">
Harvard Courses as Teaching Fellow:
<ul>
<li>STAT 303: The Art and Practice of Teaching Statistics (AY 2013-14)</li>
<li>STAT 98: Junior Tutorial (Spring 2013)</li>
<li>STAT 139: Linear Models (Fall 2012)</li>
<li>STAT 104: Quantitative Methods for Economics (Spring 2012)</li>
<li>STAT 101: Intro to Quantitative Methods for Social Sciences (Fall 2011)</li>
<li>EMR 16: Real Life Statistics (Summer 2011)</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div style="font-size: 1.25em; line-height: 1.0em">
NYU Courses as Project Advisor:
<ul>
<li>DS-GA 10060: Data Science Capstone (Fall 2015)</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div style="font-size: 1.25em; line-height: 1.0em">
Awards:
<ul>
<li>4 times awarded <a href="http://bokcenter.harvard.edu/certificates-excellence">certificate for distinction in teaching</a> by Harvard's Derek Bok Center</li>
<li><a href="http://www.stat.harvard.edu/Academics/PickardAwards/">David Pickard Memorial Teaching Fellow</a></li>
</ul>
